<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="111" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,1452,158,977]" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,400,194,220]" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
—The species is referred as a variety of 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus (1785: 1145)" authorityName="Linnaeus (1785:" authorityPageNumber="1145" authorityYear="1145" box="[859,1260,194,221]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[859,996,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">Sida ciliaris</emphasis>
Linnaeus (1785: 1145)
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hochreutiner, B. P. G." pageId="6" pageNumber="111" pagination="10 - 59" refId="ref19159" refString="Hochreutiner, B. P. G. (1902) Malvaceae novae vel minus cognitae. Annuaire du Conservatoire et du Jardin Botaniques de Geneve 6: 10 - 59." type="journal article" year="1902">Hochreutiner (1902: 35)</bibRefCitation>
. However, we adopt the 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigo, A." box="[543,718,230,256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" pagination="81 - 212" refId="ref20258" refString="Rodrigo, A. del P. (1944) Las especies argentinas y uruguayas del genero Sida (Malvaceae). Revista del Museo de La Plata (Nueva Serie), Seccion Botanica 6: 81 - 212." type="journal article" year="1944">Rodrigo (1944)</bibRefCitation>
species concept, which separates 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1825" box="[1107,1234,230,257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis box="[1107,1234,230,257]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">S. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus (1785:" authorityYear="1145" box="[1306,1414,230,257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[1306,1414,230,257]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">S. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by linear leaf blades, flowers with 
<quantity box="[500,557,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
in diameter, and mericarps with large irregular prominences (muricate) at the dorsal face (vs. suborbicular or cuneate-truncate leaves, flowers with 
<quantity box="[907,983,302,329]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
in diameter, and mericarps fine reticulate, with short spinose prominences only at the lateral angles). After analyzing herbarium materials, we believe that these diagnostic characters are sufficient to separate the two species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigo, A." box="[852,1026,374,400]" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" pagination="81 - 212" refId="ref20258" refString="Rodrigo, A. del P. (1944) Las especies argentinas y uruguayas del genero Sida (Malvaceae). Revista del Museo de La Plata (Nueva Serie), Seccion Botanica 6: 81 - 212." type="journal article" year="1944">Rodrigo (1944)</bibRefCitation>
states that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1825" box="[1153,1280,374,401]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis box="[1153,1280,374,401]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">S. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has erect habit and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus (1785:" authorityYear="1145" box="[184,292,410,437]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis box="[184,292,410,437]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">S. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
decumbent or semidecumbent habit in the field. However, we also observed individuals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1825" box="[1325,1451,410,437]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis box="[1325,1451,410,437]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">S. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with decumbent or semidecumbent habit. Therefore its habit does not serve as a diagnostic character. The species can be distinguished from 
<emphasis box="[447,621,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rodrigo" authorityYear="1937" box="[447,617,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paradoxa">Sida paradoxa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
also from section 
<emphasis box="[841,997,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">Malacroideae</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation box="[1015,1102,482,508]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
), by linear leaf blades (rarely linear-lanceolate), serrate in the upper half; flowers 
<quantity box="[720,776,518,545]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
in diameter; fruits with 7–8 mericarps (
<figureCitation box="[1225,1382,518,544]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,187,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[190,1398,187,1893]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–F. Sida anomala. A. Flower. B. Branch with flowers buds and leaves. C. Schizocarp. D. Branch leaves and stipules. E. Adaxial surface of leaf. F. Abaxial surface of leaf. G–L. Sida cerradoensis. G. Flower. H. Schizocarps and flower. I. Adaxial surface of leaf. J. Abaxial surface of leaf. K. Sulcate petiole. L. Schizocarp. M–Q. Sida confusa. M. Abaxial surface of leaf. N. Adaxial surface of leaf. O. Flower. P. Branch with schizocarp and leaves. Q. Peduncle and immature schizocarp. Photographs by Martin Grings and Marcio Verdi (O)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415489/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">Figures 1A–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1394,1443,518,544]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="111">14A</figureCitation>
) (vs. cuneate-truncate leaf blades, subentire, with three teeth at the apex; flowers 
<quantity box="[1072,1151,554,581]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="111" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
in diameter; fruits with 5 mericarps).
</paragraph>
